{"title_page": "Walter Lindsay of Balgavie", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Sir Walter Lindsay of Balgavie''' (died 25 October 1605) was a Scottish [[Roman Catholic]] intriguer.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the third son of [[David Lindsay, 9th Earl of Crawford]], by his second wife, Catherine, daughter of Sir John Campbell of Lorn and Calder. He acquired the property of Balgavie and Balgavies Castle in of [[Forfarshire]] on 20 February 1584. In 1580 he became a gentleman of the bedchamber to [[James VI of Scotland]], and also joined a group of young men who subscribed to serve the king in time of war at their own expense.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\n==Catholic convert==\nThrough the influence of the Jesuits [[James Gordon (Jesuit)|James Gordon]] and [[William Crichton (Jesuit)|William Crichton]] Lindsay became a convert to Catholicism; he said he was the first whom they induced to recant and openly profess the change of faith.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}} He kept an English Jesuit in his house, and it became a rendezvous of Catholics: his chaplain for 18 months was [[John Ingram (martyr)|John Ingram]].{{sfn|Butler|Burns|1995|p=209}} It was, he stated, mainly through his example that [[George Gordon, 1st Marquis of Huntly]], [[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll]], and [[William Douglas, 10th Earl of Angus]] were induced to make open confession of Catholicism.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\nIn 1589 Lindsay was imprisoned in [[Edinburgh Castle]] but on 29 November was conditionally released, [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]], becoming his caution that he would enter again into ward and remain there till his trial. On 19 May, for failing to appear, he was denounced as a rebel, and on 11 January 1593 he was charged, on pain of rebellion, to appear before and answer to the king and council. He failed to appear, and in 1593 the king, during a progress in the north, demolished his castle. On 30 September 1594 he was again denounced as a rebel, the special charges against him being communing with conspirators against the true religion, and open avowing of [[papistry]]. In May 1594, the [[General Assembly of the Church of Scotland|General Assembly]] having recommended that he and others should be apprehended, the king expressed his willingness to do so if possible.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\nLindsay went abroad, and probably visited Spain. Having returned to Scotland towards the end of 1598, Lindsay was again denounced: he agreed to enter into a conference with the ministers of the kirk, and to remain within the bounds of the presbytery of [[Brechin]] till he had satisfied the kirk regarding his religion. On 24 May 1599, [[Alexander Lindsay, 1st Lord Spynie]] became caution for him in five thousand [[merk (coin)|merk]]s; the presumption is that he made his peace with the kirk.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\n==Death==\nLindsay took part in the feuds of the Lindsays, and led a turbulent life. On 25 October 1605 he was murdered by his kinsman [[David Lindsay, 12th Earl of Crawford|David Lindsay, Master of Crawford]], between Brechin and the Place of Edzell.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=315}}\n\n==Works==\nLindsay had printed an ''Account of the Present State of the Catholic Religion in the Realm of Scotland in the year of our Lord one thousand five hundred and ninety-four''.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=315}}\n\n==Family==\nwith his wife Margaret Campbell, sister of David Campbell of Kethnott, Lindsay had a son, David, who succeeded him, and a daughter, Margaret, married to Adam Menzies of Boltoquhan.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=315}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |last=Butler |first=Alban  |last2=Burns |first2=Paul |year=1995 |title=Butler's Lives of the Saints|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=PBGzh1JK2gUC&pg=PA209 209] |publisher=Continuum |isbn=978-0-86012-256-2}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|first= Thomas Finlayson |last=Henderson |wstitle=Lindsay, Walter|volume=33 |pages=314&ndash;315}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lindsay, Walter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1605 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Sir Walter Lindsay of Balgavie''' (died 25 October 1605) was a Scottish [[Roman Catholic]] intriguer.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was the third son of [[David Lindsay, 9th Earl of Crawford]], by his second wife, Catherine, daughter of Sir John Campbell of Lorn and Calder. He acquired the property of Balgavie in of [[Forfarshire]] on 20 February 1584. In 1580 he became a gentleman of the bedchamber to [[James VI of Scotland]], and also joined a group of young men who subscribed to serve the king in time of war at their own expense.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\n==Catholic convert==\nThrough the influence of the Jesuits [[James Gordon (Jesuit)|James Gordon]] and [[William Crichton (Jesuit)|William Crichton]] Lindsay became a convert to Catholicism; he said he was the first whom they induced to recant and openly profess the change of faith.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}} He kept an English Jesuit in his house, and it became a rendezvous of Catholics: his chaplain for 18 months was [[John Ingram (martyr)|John Ingram]].{{sfn|Butler|Burns|1995|p=209}} It was, he stated, mainly through his example that [[George Gordon, 1st Marquis of Huntly]], [[Francis Hay, 9th Earl of Erroll]], and [[William Douglas, 10th Earl of Angus]] were induced to make open confession of Catholicism.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\nIn 1589 Lindsay was imprisoned in [[Edinburgh Castle]] but on 29 November was conditionally released, [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]], becoming his caution that he would enter again into ward and remain there till his trial. On 19 May, for failing to appear, he was denounced as a rebel, and on 11 January 1593 he was charged, on pain of rebellion, to appear before and answer to the king and council. He failed to appear, and in 1593 the king, during a progress in the north, demolished his castle. On 30 September 1594 he was again denounced as a rebel, the special charges against him being communing with conspirators against the true religion, and open avowing of [[papistry]]. In May 1594, the [[General Assembly of the Church of Scotland|General Assembly]] having recommended that he and others should be apprehended, the king expressed his willingness to do so if possible.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\nLindsay went abroad, and probably visited Spain. Having returned to Scotland towards the end of 1598, Lindsay was again denounced: he agreed to enter into a conference with the ministers of the kirk, and to remain within the bounds of the presbytery of [[Brechin]] till he had satisfied the kirk regarding his religion. On 24 May 1599, [[Alexander Lindsay, 1st Lord Spynie]] became caution for him in five thousand [[merk (coin)|merk]]s; the presumption is that he made his peace with the kirk.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=314}}\n\n==Death==\nLindsay took part in the feuds of the Lindsays, and led a turbulent life. On 25 October 1605 he was murdered by his kinsman [[David Lindsay, 12th Earl of Crawford|David Lindsay, Master of Crawford]], between Brechin and the Place of Edzell.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=315}}\n\n==Works==\nLindsay had printed an ''Account of the Present State of the Catholic Religion in the Realm of Scotland in the year of our Lord one thousand five hundred and ninety-four''.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=315}}\n\n==Family==\nwith his wife Margaret Campbell, sister of David Campbell of Kethnott, Lindsay had a son, David, who succeeded him, and a daughter, Margaret, married to Adam Menzies of Boltoquhan.{{sfn|Henderson|1893|p=315}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv |last=Butler |first=Alban  |last2=Burns |first2=Paul |year=1995 |title=Butler's Lives of the Saints|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=PBGzh1JK2gUC&pg=PA209 209] |publisher=Continuum |isbn=978-0-86012-256-2}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|first= Thomas Finlayson |last=Henderson |wstitle=Lindsay, Walter|volume=33 |pages=314&ndash;315}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lindsay, Walter}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1605 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Lindsay_of_Balgavie"}
{"title_page": "List of entertainment events at the O2 Arena", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{cleanup|date=November 2016|reason=There are too many citations for certain events, keeping only 1 reliable source for each event will suffice.}}\n\nSince opening in 2007, [[The O2 Arena]] has hosted hundreds of concerts from UK and international superstars. It was named the ''World's Best Venue'' by Pollstar in 2009. It has been named as the busiest indoor arena in the world with over 1,819,487 tickets sold in 2015 alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pollstarpro.com/files/charts2015/2015YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues.pdf|title=2015 Year End Worldwide Ticket Sales Top 200 Arena Venues|access-date=25 September 2016|archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160517203229/http://www.pollstarpro.com/files/charts2015/2015YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues.pdf|archive-date=17 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBelow is a list of artists that have performed at the arena since its opening in 2007.\n\n==2007 \u2013 2010==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=October 2016}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n\n|-\n\n! colspan=\"3\"|Entertainment events held at the O2 Arena\n\n|-\n! width=100| Date\n\n! width=150| Artists\n\n! width=300| Events\n\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#ddd;\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|'''2007'''\n\n|-\n| 23 June\n\n| [[Dermot O'Leary]] (Host)<br>[[Philip Anschutz|Anschutz]]<br>[[Peter Kay]]<br>[[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]]<br>[[Kaiser Chiefs]]<br>[[Basement Jaxx]]<br>[[Snow Patrol]]\n| Opening Ceremony of the O2 Arena\n|-\n| 24 June\n| [[Bon Jovi]]\n| [[Lost Highway (Bon Jovi album)|Lost Highway]] Promotional Show\n|-\n| 28 June\n| [[Snow Patrol]]\n| [[Eyes Open Tour]]\n|-\n| 4 July\n| rowspan=5| [[Justin Timberlake]]\n| rowspan=5| [[FutureSex/LoveShow]]\n\n|-\n| 5 July\n|-\n| 7 July\n|-\n| 8 July\n|-\n\n| 10 July\n\n|-\n\n| 18 July\n| [[Barbra Streisan