{"title_page": "Royal Academy of Engineering", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| name          = \n| former name   = \n| bgcolor       = <!-- header background color -->\n| fgcolor       = <!-- header text color -->\n| image         = Royal_Academy_of_Engineering_Logo,_green,_October_2013.jpg\n| image_border  = \n| size          = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt           = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption       = \n| map           = <!-- optional -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption      = <!-- optional -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = \n| motto         = \"To bring engineering to the heart of society\"\n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = June 1976\n| extinction    = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n| type          = <!-- [[Governmental organization|GO]], [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]], [[Intergovernmental organization|IGO]], [[International nongovernmental organization|INGO]], etc -->\n| status        = Royal Charter\n| purpose       = To advance and promote excellence in engineering\n| headquarters  = [[London]], {{postcode|SW|1}}\n| location      = {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom \n| coords        = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n| region_served = \n| membership    = 3 Royal Fellows, 1,541 Fellows\n| language      = <!-- official languages -->\n| general       = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title  = President\n| leader_name   = [[Jim McDonald (electrical engineer)|Professor Sir James McDonald]] {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSE|FREng}}\n| leader_title2 = CEO\n| leader_name2  = Dr [[Hayaatun Sillem]]\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| main_organ    = Board of Trustees\n| parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n| affiliations  = <!-- if any -->\n| budget        = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website       = {{URL|http://www.raeng.org.uk}}\n| remarks       = \n}}The '''Royal Academy of Engineering''' ('''RAEng''') is the UK's [[national academy]] of [[engineering]].\n\nThe Academy was founded in June 1976 as the '''Fellowship of Engineering''' with support from [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], who became the first Senior Fellow and, {{As of|2020|lc=on}}, remains so. The Fellowship was incorporated and granted a [[Royal Charter]] on 17 May 1983 and became the Royal Academy of Engineering on 16 March 1992. It is governed according to the Charter and associated Statutes and Regulations (as amended from time to time).<ref>{{cite web|title=RAEng: Charter, Statutes and Regulations|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/publications/other/raeng-charter-statutes-regulations|accessdate=18 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmselect/cmsctech/774/77405.htm |title=The Royal Academy of Engineering |publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] |date={{Format date|2002|9|1|df=yes}} |accessdate={{Format date|2012|12|5|df=yes}}}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nConceived in the late 1960s, during the Apollo space programme and [[Harold Wilson]]\u2019s espousal of \u2018[[white heat of technology]]\u2019, the Fellowship of Engineering was born in the year of Concorde's first commercial flight.<ref>[http://www.britishairways.com/concorde/aboutconcorde.html#facts_figures Celebrating Concorde]. Britishairways.com. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nThe Fellowship's first meeting, at Buckingham Palace on 11 June 1976, enrolled 126 of the UK's leading engineers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/founder_fellows/default.htm |title=Founder Fellows |publisher=Royal Academy of Engineering |date={{Format date|1976|6|10|df=yes}} |accessdate={{Format date|2012|12|5|df=yes}}}}</ref> The first fellows included [[Frank Whittle|Air Commodore Sir Frank Whittle]], the jet engine developer, the structural engineer [[Ove Arup|Sir Ove Arup]], radar pioneer [[George G. Macfarlane|Sir George MacFarlane]], the inventor of the bouncing bomb, [[Barnes Wallis|Sir Barnes Wallis]], and father of the UK computer industry [[Maurice Wilkes|Sir Maurice Wilkes]]. The Fellowship's first President, [[Christopher Hinton, Baron Hinton of Bankside|Lord Hinton]], had driven the UK's supremacy in nuclear power.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/earlydays.htm History of The Academy - Early Days]. Raeng.org.uk (1976-06-11). Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nThe Fellowship focused on championing excellence in all fields of engineering. Activities began in earnest in the mid-1970s with the Distinction lecture series, now known as the Hinton lectures. The Fellowship was asked to advise the Department of Industry for the first time and the Academy became host and presenter of the MacRobert Award.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/establish.htm History of The Academy - 1976\u20131981: Establishing a track record]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the Fellowship received its own Royal Charter along with its first government grant-in-aid. At the same time it also received significant industrial funding, initiated its research programme to build bridges between academia and industry and opened its doors to International and Honorary Fellows.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/growing.htm History of The Academy - 1981\u20131986: Growing influence and activities]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, the Academy launched its first major initiative in education, Engineering Education Continuum, which evolved into the BEST Programme<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20020218224550/http://www.raeng.org.uk/education/best.htm] </ref> and Shape the Future and Tomorrow's Engineers.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071011212837/http://www.raeng.org.uk/education/stf/default.htm] </ref>\n\nThe Academy's increasing level of influence \u2013 in policy, research and education \u2013 was recognised when it was granted a royal title and became The Royal Academy of Engineering in 1992.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/fromfellow.htm History of The Academy - 1991\u20131996: From Fellowship to Royal Academy]. Raeng.org.uk (1992-07-02). Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\n[[File:REng-Old-Logo.jpg|right|thumb|upright|The old logo of UK Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n\n==Logo==\nThe Academy's current logo<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raeng.org.uk/publications/visual-identity-style-guide/logos|title= Academy logos}}</ref> is inspired by the Neolithic hand-axe, humans' first technological advance, which was taken to be a symbol appropriate to the Academy, supposedly representative of the ever-changing relationship between humanity and technology.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/housestyle/default.htm Visual Identity Guidelines]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref> The old logo is no longer in use but shown here for historical reasons.\n\n==Prince Philip House==\nThe Academy's premises, 3-4 [[Carlton House Terrace]], are in a [[Grade I listed building]] overlooking [[St James's Park]], designed by celebrated architect [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]] and owned by the [[Crown Estates]]. The Academy shares the Terrace with two of its sister academies, the [[British Academy]] and the [[Royal Society]] as well as other institutes.\n\nThe building was renamed Prince Philip House,<ref>[http://www.princephiliphouse.com/ Home | Prince Philip House]</ref> in honour of the Senior Fellow, after renovation works were completed in 2012. Prince Philip House is also available for venue hire for meetings or events.\n\n== Presidents of the Royal Academy of Engineering ==\nThe President of the Royal Academy of Engineering, the elected officer of the Academy, presides over meetings of the Council. The President is elected for a single term of not more than five years.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Years !! colspan=2|President\n|-\n| 1976-1981 || [[Christopher Hinton, Baron Hinton of Bankside]] || [[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 1981-1986 || [[Robin Inskip, 2nd Viscount Caldecote]] ||[[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSC]], [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]]\n|-\n| 1986-1991 || [[Sir Denis Rooke]] || [[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Royal Society|FRS]],\n|-\n| 1991-1996 || Sir William Barlow || [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]]\n|-\n| 1996-2001 || [[David Davies (electrical engineer)|Sir David Davies]] ||[[Knight Bachelor|Kt]],  [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2001-2006 || [[Alec Broers, Baron Broers]] ||[[Knight Bachelor|Kt]],  [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2006-2011 || [[John Browne, Baron Browne of Madingley]] || [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2011-2014 || [[John Parker (businessman)|Sir John Parker]] || [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]],  [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]],  [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]]\n|-\n| 2014-2019 || [[Ann Dowling|Professor Dame Ann Dowling]] || [[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2019- || [[Jim McDonald (electrical engineer)|Sir Jim McDonald]] ||[[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]] \n|}\n\n==Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering==\nThe Fellowship currently includes over 1,500 engineers from all sectors and disciplines of engineering. The Fellows, distinguished by the title '''Fellow of The Royal Academy of Engineering''' and the postnominal designation '''FREng''', lead, guide and contribute to the Academy's work and provide expertise.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/fellowslist.htm The Fellowship - List of Fellows]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nUp to 60 engineers are elected each year by their peers. Honorary and International Fellows who have made exceptional contributions to engineering are also elected and are entitled to use respectively the designatory letters '''HonFREng''' and '''FREng''' after their name.<ref>[https://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/the-fellowship The Fellowship]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved 12 December 2017.</ref>\n\nThe criteria for election are stated in the charter, statutes, and regulations document.<ref>https://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/what-we-do/charter-and-statutes</ref> The essential attributes of excellence in engineering \ninclude:\n\n* '''Organization leaders:''' those with full responsibility on technical decisions\n\n* '''Top Engineers, academics or researchers:''' whose work have resulted in new products, important processes or practices.\n\n* '''Top Engineers:''' those who have made outstanding contributions to major projects.\n\n* '''Engineering department leaders:''' those who have demonstrated significant personal engineering achievements \n\nThe '''Royal Fellows''' of the Academy are Prince Philip, the [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent|Duke of Kent]], and [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]].\n<gallery>\nImage:25.Jun.2015 Prince Philip in Frankfurt.jpg|{{centre|Prince Philip}}\nImage:HRH The Duke of Kent 5 Allan Warrenjpg.jpg|{{centre|The Duke of Kent}}\nImage:Princess Anne October 2015.jpg|{{centre|Princess Anne}}\n</gallery>\n\n{{Details|List of female Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering}}\n{{Details|List of International Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering}}\n\n==Activities==\nThe Academy is instrumental in two policy alliances set up in 2009 to provide coherent advice on engineering education and policy across the profession: Education for Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationforengineering.org.uk/|title=Education for Engineering (E4E)|website=Education for Engineering (E4E)|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> and ''Engineering the Future''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.engineeringthefuture.co.uk|title=Engineering the Future|website=Engineering the Future|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Academy is one of four agencies that receive funding from the UK's Department for Business Innovation & Skills for activities that support government policy on public understanding of science and engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/2010-to-2015-government-policy-public-understanding-of-science-and-engineering/2010-to-2015-government-policy-public-understanding-of-science-and-engineering|title=2010 to 2015 government policy: public understanding of science and engineering|website=Gov.uk|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs part of its programme to communicate the benefits and value of engineering to society, the Academy publishes a quarterly magazine, Ingenia[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034924/http://www.ingenia.org.uk/Online]. The Academy says that Ingenia is written for a non-specialist audience and is \"aimed at all those with an interest in engineering, whether working in business and industry, government, academia or the financial community\". The Academy also makes Ingenia available to A-Level students in 3,000 schools in the UK. \n\n==Diversity==\nThe Academy strives to ensure that the pool of candidates for election to The Fellowship better reflects the diverse make-up of society as a whole. It set up the Proactive Membership Committee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213172155/http://raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 December 2011|title=Council and Committees: Proactive Membership Committee|date=13 December 2011|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> in 2008 to identify and support the nomination of candidates from underrepresented areas, with the aim of boosting the number of women candidates, engineers from industry and Small and Medium Enterprises, those from emerging technologies and ethnically diverse backgrounds.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm Council and Committees: Proactive Membership Committee] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213172155/http://raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm |date=2011-12-13 }}. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\n== Awards and prizes ==\n* With the support of the [[Worshipful Company of Engineers]], the Academy manages the annual Royal Academy of Engineering [[MacRobert Award]], the premier prize for UK innovation in engineering. First presented in 1969, the award honours  the winning company with a gold medal and the team members with a prize of \u00a350,000.\n* The Academy oversees the awarding of the [[Queen Elizabeth Prize for Engineering]]. The QEPrize is an international, \u00a31 million engineering prize that \"rewards and celebrates the engineers responsible for a ground-breaking innovation that has been of global benefit to humanity\". The objective of the prize is to \"raise the public profile of engineering and to inspire young people to become engineers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/grants-and-prizes/prizes-and-medals/other-awards/queen-elizabeth-prize-for-engineering|title=Queen Elizabeth Prize for Engineering - Royal Academy of Engineering|website=Raeng.org.uk|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n* The Academy's Sir George Macfarlane Medal is an annual award that \"recognises a UK engineer who has demonstrated excellence in the early stage of their career\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140810042633/http://www.raeng.org.uk/grants-and-prizes/prizes-and-medals/individual-awards/sir-george-mac-farlane-award] </ref>\n* The [[President's Medal (Royal Academy of Engineering)|President's Medal]]\n* The [[Prince Philip Medal]], named after [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], and \"awarded periodically to an engineer of any nationality who has made an exceptional contribution to engineering as a whole through practice, management or education.\"<ref>RAE: [http://www.raeng.org.uk/prizes/philip/default.htm Prince Philip Medal]</ref>\n* Chair in Emerging Technologies, a scheme providing long-term support to visionary researchers in developing technologies with high potential to deliver economic and social benefit to the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.raeng.org.uk/news/news-releases/2018/april/academy-funds-global-research-visionaries-to-advan|title=Academy funds global research visionaries to advance emerging technologies|last=|first=|date=10 April 2018|website=Royal Academy of Engineering|access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Engineering Development Trust]]\n*[[Engineering]]\n*[[Glossary of engineering]]\n*[[Royal Academy of Engineering International Medal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Science and technology in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Scientific organizations established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Engineering societies based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National academies of engineering|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Royal Academy of Engineering| ]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the City of Westminster]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| name          = \n| former name   = \n| bgcolor       = <!-- header background color -->\n| fgcolor       = <!-- header text color -->\n| image         = Royal_Academy_of_Engineering_Logo,_green,_October_2013.jpg\n| image_border  = \n| size          = <!-- default 200px -->\n| alt           = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption       = \n| map           = <!-- optional -->\n| msize         = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px -->\n| malt          = <!-- map alt text -->\n| mcaption      = <!-- optional -->\n| map2          = \n| abbreviation  = \n| motto         = \"To bring engineering to the heart of society\"\n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| formation     = June 1976\n| extinction    = <!-- date of extinction, optional -->\n| type          = <!-- [[Governmental organization|GO]], [[Non-governmental organization|NGO]], [[Intergovernmental organization|IGO]], [[International nongovernmental organization|INGO]], etc -->\n| status        = Royal Charter\n| purpose       = To advance and promote excellence in engineering\n| headquarters  = [[London]], {{postcode|SW|1}}\n| location      = {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom \n| coords        = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template -->\n| region_served = \n| membership    = 3 Royal Fellows, 1,541 Fellows\n| language      = <!-- official languages -->\n| general       = <!-- Secretary General -->\n| leader_title  = President\n| leader_name   = [[Jim McDonald (electrical engineer)|Professor Sir James McDonald]] {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSE|FREng}}\n| leader_title2 = CEO\n| leader_name2  = Dr [[Hayaatun Sillem]]\n| leader_title3 = \n| leader_name3  = \n| leader_title4 = \n| leader_name4  = \n| main_organ    = Board of Trustees\n| parent_organization = <!-- if one -->\n| affiliations  = <!-- if any -->\n| budget        = \n| num_staff     = \n| num_volunteers = \n| website       = {{URL|http://www.raeng.org.uk}}\n| remarks       = \n}}The '''Royal Academy of Engineering''' (RAEng) is the UK's [[national academy]] of [[engineering]].\n\nThe Academy was founded in June 1976 as the '''Fellowship of Engineering''' with support from [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], who became the first Senior Fellow and, {{As of|2020|lc=on}}, remains so. The Fellowship was incorporated and granted a [[Royal Charter]] on 17 May 1983 and became the Royal Academy of Engineering on 16 March 1992. It is governed according to the Charter and associated Statutes and Regulations (as amended from time to time).<ref>{{cite web|title=RAEng: Charter, Statutes and Regulations|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/publications/other/raeng-charter-statutes-regulations|accessdate=18 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmselect/cmsctech/774/77405.htm |title=The Royal Academy of Engineering |publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] |date={{Format date|2002|9|1|df=yes}} |accessdate={{Format date|2012|12|5|df=yes}}}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nConceived in the late 1960s, during the Apollo space programme and [[Harold Wilson]]\u2019s espousal of \u2018[[white heat of technology]]\u2019, the Fellowship of Engineering was born in the year of Concorde's first commercial flight.<ref>[http://www.britishairways.com/concorde/aboutconcorde.html#facts_figures Celebrating Concorde]. Britishairways.com. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nThe Fellowship's first meeting, at Buckingham Palace on 11 June 1976, enrolled 126 of the UK's leading engineers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/founder_fellows/default.htm |title=Founder Fellows |publisher=Royal Academy of Engineering |date={{Format date|1976|6|10|df=yes}} |accessdate={{Format date|2012|12|5|df=yes}}}}</ref> The first fellows included [[Frank Whittle|Air Commodore Sir Frank Whittle]], the jet engine developer, the structural engineer [[Ove Arup|Sir Ove Arup]], radar pioneer [[George G. Macfarlane|Sir George MacFarlane]], the inventor of the bouncing bomb, [[Barnes Wallis|Sir Barnes Wallis]], and father of the UK computer industry [[Maurice Wilkes|Sir Maurice Wilkes]]. The Fellowship's first President, [[Christopher Hinton, Baron Hinton of Bankside|Lord Hinton]], had driven the UK's supremacy in nuclear power.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/earlydays.htm History of The Academy - Early Days]. Raeng.org.uk (1976-06-11). Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nThe Fellowship focused on championing excellence in all fields of engineering. Activities began in earnest in the mid-1970s with the Distinction lecture series, now known as the Hinton lectures. The Fellowship was asked to advise the Department of Industry for the first time and the Academy became host and presenter of the MacRobert Award.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/establish.htm History of The Academy - 1976\u20131981: Establishing a track record]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, the Fellowship received its own Royal Charter along with its first government grant-in-aid. At the same time it also received significant industrial funding, initiated its research programme to build bridges between academia and industry and opened its doors to International and Honorary Fellows.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/growing.htm History of The Academy - 1981\u20131986: Growing influence and activities]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, the Academy launched its first major initiative in education, Engineering Education Continuum, which evolved into the BEST Programme<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20020218224550/http://www.raeng.org.uk/education/best.htm] </ref> and Shape the Future and Tomorrow's Engineers.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071011212837/http://www.raeng.org.uk/education/stf/default.htm] </ref>\n\nThe Academy's increasing level of influence \u2013 in policy, research and education \u2013 was recognised when it was granted a royal title and became The Royal Academy of Engineering in 1992.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/history/fromfellow.htm History of The Academy - 1991\u20131996: From Fellowship to Royal Academy]. Raeng.org.uk (1992-07-02). Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\n[[File:REng-Old-Logo.jpg|right|thumb|upright|The old logo of UK Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n\n==Logo==\nThe Academy's current logo<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.raeng.org.uk/publications/visual-identity-style-guide/logos|title= Academy logos}}</ref> is inspired by the Neolithic hand-axe, humans' first technological advance, which was taken to be a symbol appropriate to the Academy, supposedly representative of the ever-changing relationship between humanity and technology.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/housestyle/default.htm Visual Identity Guidelines]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref> The old logo is no longer in use but shown here for historical reasons.\n\n==Prince Philip House==\nThe Academy's premises, 3-4 [[Carlton House Terrace]], are in a [[Grade I listed building]] overlooking [[St James's Park]], designed by celebrated architect [[John Nash (architect)|John Nash]] and owned by the [[Crown Estates]]. The Academy shares the Terrace with two of its sister academies, the [[British Academy]] and the [[Royal Society]] as well as other institutes.\n\nThe building was renamed Prince Philip House,<ref>[http://www.princephiliphouse.com/ Home | Prince Philip House]</ref> in honour of the Senior Fellow, after renovation works were completed in 2012. Prince Philip House is also available for venue hire for meetings or events.\n\n== Presidents of the Royal Academy of Engineering ==\nThe President of the Royal Academy of Engineering, the elected officer of the Academy, presides over meetings of the Council. The President is elected for a single term of not more than five years.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Years !! colspan=2|President\n|-\n| 1976-1981 || [[Christopher Hinton, Baron Hinton of Bankside]] || [[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 1981-1986 || [[Robin Inskip, 2nd Viscount Caldecote]] ||[[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|DSC]], [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]]\n|-\n| 1986-1991 || [[Sir Denis Rooke]] || [[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Royal Society|FRS]],\n|-\n| 1991-1996 || Sir William Barlow || [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]]\n|-\n| 1996-2001 || [[David Davies (electrical engineer)|Sir David Davies]] ||[[Knight Bachelor|Kt]],  [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2001-2006 || [[Alec Broers, Baron Broers]] ||[[Knight Bachelor|Kt]],  [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2006-2011 || [[John Browne, Baron Browne of Madingley]] || [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2011-2014 || [[John Parker (businessman)|Sir John Parker]] || [[Order of the British Empire|GBE]],  [[Knight Bachelor|Kt]],  [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]]\n|-\n| 2014-2019 || [[Ann Dowling|Professor Dame Ann Dowling]] || [[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]\n|-\n| 2019- || [[Jim McDonald (electrical engineer)|Sir Jim McDonald]] ||[[Knight Bachelor|Kt]], [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering|FREng]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh|FRSE]] \n|}\n\n==Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering==\nThe Fellowship currently includes over 1,500 engineers from all sectors and disciplines of engineering. The Fellows, distinguished by the title '''Fellow of The Royal Academy of Engineering''' and the postnominal designation '''FREng''', lead, guide and contribute to the Academy's work and provide expertise.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/fellowslist.htm The Fellowship - List of Fellows]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\nUp to 60 engineers are elected each year by their peers. Honorary and International Fellows who have made exceptional contributions to engineering are also elected and are entitled to use respectively the designatory letters '''HonFREng''' and '''FREng''' after their name.<ref>[https://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/the-fellowship The Fellowship]. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved 12 December 2017.</ref>\n\nThe criteria for election are stated in the charter, statutes, and regulations document.<ref>https://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/what-we-do/charter-and-statutes</ref> The essential attributes of excellence in engineering \ninclude:\n\n* '''Organization leaders:''' those with full responsibility on technical decisions\n\n* '''Top Engineers, academics or researchers:''' whose work have resulted in new products, important processes or practices.\n\n* '''Top Engineers:''' those who have made outstanding contributions to major projects.\n\n* '''Engineering department leaders:''' those who have demonstrated significant personal engineering achievements \n\nThe '''Royal Fellows''' of the Academy are Prince Philip, the [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent|Duke of Kent]], and [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]].\n<gallery>\nImage:25.Jun.2015 Prince Philip in Frankfurt.jpg|{{centre|Prince Philip}}\nImage:HRH The Duke of Kent 5 Allan Warrenjpg.jpg|{{centre|The Duke of Kent}}\nImage:Princess Anne October 2015.jpg|{{centre|Princess Anne}}\n</gallery>\n\n{{Details|List of female Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering}}\n{{Details|List of International Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering}}\n\n==Activities==\nThe Academy is instrumental in two policy alliances set up in 2009 to provide coherent advice on engineering education and policy across the profession: Education for Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.educationforengineering.org.uk/|title=Education for Engineering (E4E)|website=Education for Engineering (E4E)|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> and ''Engineering the Future''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.engineeringthefuture.co.uk|title=Engineering the Future|website=Engineering the Future|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Academy is one of four agencies that receive funding from the UK's Department for Business Innovation & Skills for activities that support government policy on public understanding of science and engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/2010-to-2015-government-policy-public-understanding-of-science-and-engineering/2010-to-2015-government-policy-public-understanding-of-science-and-engineering|title=2010 to 2015 government policy: public understanding of science and engineering|website=Gov.uk|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs part of its programme to communicate the benefits and value of engineering to society, the Academy publishes a quarterly magazine, Ingenia[https://web.archive.org/web/20150924034924/http://www.ingenia.org.uk/Online]. The Academy says that Ingenia is written for a non-specialist audience and is \"aimed at all those with an interest in engineering, whether working in business and industry, government, academia or the financial community\". The Academy also makes Ingenia available to A-Level students in 3,000 schools in the UK. \n\n==Diversity==\nThe Academy strives to ensure that the pool of candidates for election to The Fellowship better reflects the diverse make-up of society as a whole. It set up the Proactive Membership Committee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213172155/http://raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 December 2011|title=Council and Committees: Proactive Membership Committee|date=13 December 2011|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref> in 2008 to identify and support the nomination of candidates from underrepresented areas, with the aim of boosting the number of women candidates, engineers from industry and Small and Medium Enterprises, those from emerging technologies and ethnically diverse backgrounds.<ref>[http://www.raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm Council and Committees: Proactive Membership Committee] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213172155/http://raeng.org.uk/about/fellowship/council/pro_active_membership.htm |date=2011-12-13 }}. Raeng.org.uk. Retrieved on 2013-08-13.</ref>\n\n== Awards and prizes ==\n* With the support of the [[Worshipful Company of Engineers]], the Academy manages the annual Royal Academy of Engineering [[MacRobert Award]], the premier prize for UK innovation in engineering. First presented in 1969, the award honours  the winning company with a gold medal and the team members with a prize of \u00a350,000.\n* The Academy oversees the awarding of the [[Queen Elizabeth Prize for Engineering]]. The QEPrize is an international, \u00a31 million engineering prize that \"rewards and celebrates the engineers responsible for a ground-breaking innovation that has been of global benefit to humanity\". The objective of the prize is to \"raise the public profile of engineering and to inspire young people to become engineers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/grants-and-prizes/prizes-and-medals/other-awards/queen-elizabeth-prize-for-engineering|title=Queen Elizabeth Prize for Engineering - Royal Academy of Engineering|website=Raeng.org.uk|accessdate=7 September 2018}}</ref>\n* The Academy's Sir George Macfarlane Medal is an annual award that \"recognises a UK engineer who has demonstrated excellence in the early stage of their career\".<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140810042633/http://www.raeng.org.uk/grants-and-prizes/prizes-and-medals/individual-awards/sir-george-mac-farlane-award] </ref>\n* The [[President's Medal (Royal Academy of Engineering)|President's Medal]]\n* The [[Prince Philip Medal]], named after [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], and \"awarded periodically to an engineer of any nationality who has made an exceptional contribution to engineering as a whole through practice, management or education.\"<ref>RAE: [http://www.raeng.org.uk/prizes/philip/default.htm Prince Philip Medal]</ref>\n* Chair in Emerging Technologies, a scheme providing long-term support to visionary researchers in developing technologies with high potential to deliver economic and social benefit to the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.raeng.org.uk/news/news-releases/2018/april/academy-funds-global-research-visionaries-to-advan|title=Academy funds global research visionaries to advance emerging technologies|last=|first=|date=10 April 2018|website=Royal Academy of Engineering|access-date=11 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Engineering Development Trust]]\n*[[Engineering]]\n*[[Glossary of engineering]]\n*[[Royal Academy of Engineering International Medal]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Science and technology in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Scientific organizations established in 1976]]\n[[Category:Engineering societies based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National academies of engineering|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Royal Academy of Engineering| ]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the City of Westminster]]\n", "name_user": "Me, Myself, and I are Here", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Academy_of_Engineering"}
{"title_page": "Pedro L\u00f3pez (serial killer)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name = Pedro L\u00f3pez\n| image = Pedro L\u00f3pez (asesino serial).png\n| caption = Mug shot\n| birth_name = Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez\n| alias = The Monster of the [[Andes]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1948|10|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Isabel, Tolima|Santa Isabel]], [[Tolima Department]], [[Colombia]]\n| victims = Convicted of 3,<ref name=\"AP\" /> confessed to 300+\n| beginyear = 1969\n| endyear = 2002\n| apprehended = 9 March 1980 (first)\n| sentence = 16 years (Ecuador); freed after 14 years; committed to hospital (Colombia); freed after 1 year\n| conviction = [[Motor vehicle theft]],<br>[[murder]]\n| country = [[Colombia]],<br>[[Ecuador]],<br>[[Peru]]\n| criminal status = Unknown\n}}\n'''Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez''' (born 8 October 1948<ref name=\"bio.com\" />) is a [[Colombia]]n [[serial killer]], who was sentenced for killing 110 girls, but who claimed to have [[rape]]d and killed more than 300 girls across [[Colombia]], [[Peru]] and [[Ecuador]]. Aside from uncited local accounts, L\u00f3pez's crimes first received international attention from an interview conducted by Ron Laytner, a longtime freelance photojournalist who reported interviewing L\u00f3pez in his [[San Juan de Ambato|Ambato]] prison cell in 1980.\n\nLaytner's interviews were widely published, first in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' on Sunday, 13 July 1980, then in the ''[[Toronto Sun]]'' and ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'' on 21 July 1980, and over the years in many other North American papers and foreign publications, including the ''[[National Enquirer]]''. Apart from Laytner's account and two brief [[Associated Press]] wire reports,<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|url=http://users.erols.com/mwhite28/lopez_ap.htm |title=Who is Pedro Lopez? |accessdate=2013-08-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021224003/http://users.erols.com/mwhite28/lopez_ap.htm |archivedate=21 October 2007 }}</ref> the story was published in ''The World's Most Infamous Murders'' by Boar and Blundell,<ref>The World's Most Infamous Murders by Roger Boar and Nigel Blundell \u2013 Octopus London 1983 {{ISBN|0-600-57008-8}} pages 116\u2013118</ref> and has found its way into many serial murder anthologies, both in print and online.\n\nAccording to Laytner's story,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.editinternational.com/read.php?id=47ddbd11af56e |title=Worst Serial Killer Released |publisher=Edit International |accessdate=2013-08-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710172222/http://www.editinternational.com/read.php?id=47ddbd11af56e# |archive-date=10 July 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> L\u00f3pez became known as the '''Monster of the Andes''' in 1980, when he led police to 53 graves in [[Ecuador]]. The victims were all girls 12 years of age. In 1983, he was found guilty of the murder of 110 girls in [[Ecuador]]. He further confessed to an additional 240 murders in [[Peru]] and [[Colombia]].\n\n==Early life==\nL\u00f3pez's mother was a prostitute named Benilda L\u00f3pez De Casteneda. According to L\u00f3pez, witnessing acts of prostitution while growing up had disturbing effects on his psyche. Subsequently, his mother caught him fondling his younger sister in 1957, when he was eight years old, and evicted him from the family home.<ref name=\"NineNews\">{{cite web |last1=Pearson |first1=Nick |title=World's second worst serial killer walked free from prison |url=https://www.9news.com.au/world/pedro-lopez-worlds-second-worst-serial-killer-walked-free-from-prison/2be19c5c-95c5-44e2-8dd1-3253319a34e5 |website=Nine News |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=5 December 2018}}</ref> Following this, L\u00f3pez fled to [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia's capital city. He says he was picked up by a man, taken to a deserted house and repeatedly sodomized. At age twelve, he was taken in by an American family and enrolled in a school for orphans. He ran away after two years because he was allegedly molested by a male teacher. An alternative account says he ran away with a teacher. At 18, he stole cars for a living and sold the cars to local [[chop shop]]s.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Murders==\nDuring his incarceration for car theft, L\u00f3pez claimed he was brutally gang-raped<ref name=\"NineNews\"/> and that he hunted down his rapists and killed the most brutal while still in prison. He said that after his jail term, he started murdering young girls in Peru. He claimed that, by 1978, he had killed over 100 of them and that he had been caught by a native tribe, who were preparing to execute him, when an American Christian missionary intervened and persuaded them to hand him over to the state police. The police soon released him. He said he moved to Colombia and later Ecuador, killing about three girls a week. L\u00f3pez said: \"I like the girls in Ecuador; they are more gentle and trusting. More innocent.\"\n\n==Arrest==\nL\u00f3pez was arrested when an attempted abduction failed and he was trapped by market traders. The [[Associated Press]] (AP) reported that he was arrested in March 1980, and that he confessed to killing 103 girls, including 53 whose bodies had been found. In January 1981, he was convicted of three murders, and had confessed to three hundred [[sexual assault]]s and stranglings.<ref name=\"AP\" /> The police only believed his confessions when a flash flood uncovered a mass grave containing many of his victims.<!-- or according to the near-contemporary news article one grave was exposed by a flash flood - or according to A&E the flash flood was before his arrest--> \n\n==Release==\nAccording to the BBC, L\u00f3pez \"was arrested in 1980, but was freed by the government in Ecuador at the end of [1998].\"  In an interview from his prison cell, L\u00f3pez described himself as \"the man of the century\" and said he was being released for \"good behavior.\" An A&E ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'' documentary reported that he was released from an Ecuadorian prison on 31 August 1994, then rearrested  as an illegal immigrant and handed over to Colombian authorities, who charged him with a 20-year-old murder. He was declared insane and held in the psychiatric wing of a Bogot\u00e1 hospital. In 1998, he was declared sane and released on $50 bail, subject to certain conditions. He later absconded. The same documentary says that [[Interpol]] released an advisory for his rearrest by Colombian authorities over a fresh murder in 2002,<ref name=\"A&E\">{{Cite video|title=The Monster of the Andes|date=2004|ISBN=0-7670-7897-7|publisher=A&E Television Networks|author=Carlina Ramon; Maria Masabanda Inde; Carlos J\u00e1come; Pat Brennan}}</ref> and he is currently wanted by the police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vocal.media/criminal/why-did-they-free-pedro-lopez-the-monster-of-the-andes|title=Why Did They Free Pedro L\u00f3pez, the Monster of the Andes?|website=Criminal|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\nThere is currently a shortage of information regarding L\u00f3pez. His whereabouts are unknown as of 2020.<ref name=\"bio.com\">{{cite web |url= http://www.biography.com/people/pedro-alonso-lopez-12103226 |title= Pedro Alonzo Lopez Biography |website= [[biography.com]] |date= 2018-01-31 |accessdate= 2018-01-31 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161210235245/http://www.biography.com/people/pedro-alonso-lopez-12103226# |archive-date= 10 December 2016 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Coverage==\nThe 2006 edition of the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' credited Lopez as being the \"most prolific serial killer\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-prolific-serial-killer|title=Most prolific serial killer|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216093053/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-prolific-serial-killer |archive-date=2015-02-16}}</ref> The listing was removed after complaints that it made a competition out of murder, as well as comments that it overlooked killers such as [[Thug Behram]], who reportedly murdered around 900 people in India.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=k5FY0LJL6NkC</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of serial killers by number of victims]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez, Pedro}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:1980s murders in Colombia]]\n[[Category:1980s murders in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:1983 crimes in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:1983 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:1990s murders in Colombia]]\n[[Category:1998 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:2000s murders in Colombia]]\n[[Category:2002 crimes in Colombia]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Colombian murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Colombian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Colombian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Colombian prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Colombian rapists]]\n[[Category:Colombian serial killers]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Colombia]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox serial killer\n| name        = Pedro L\u00f3pez\n| image       = Pedro L\u00f3pez (asesino serial).png\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez\n| alias       = The Monster of the [[Andes]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1948|10|8}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Isabel, Tolima|Santa Isabel]], [[Tolima Department]], [[Colombia]]\n| victims     = Convicted of 3,<ref name=\"AP\" /> confessed to 300+\n| beginyear   = 1969\n| endyear     = 2002\n| apprehended = 9 March 1980 (first)\n| sentence    = 16 years (Ecuador); freed after 14 years; committed to hospital (Colombia); freed after 1 year\n| conviction  = [[Motor vehicle theft]],<br>[[murder]]\n| country     = [[Colombia]],<br>[[Ecuador]],<br>[[Peru]]\n| criminal status = Unknown\n}}\n'''Pedro Alonso L\u00f3pez''' (born 8 October 1948<ref name=\"bio.com\" />) is a [[Colombia]]n [[serial killer]], who was sentenced for killing 110 girls, but who claimed to have [[rape]]d and killed more than 300 girls across [[Colombia]], [[Peru]] and [[Ecuador]]. Aside from uncited local accounts, L\u00f3pez's crimes first received international attention from an interview conducted by Ron Laytner, a longtime freelance photojournalist who reported interviewing L\u00f3pez in his [[San Juan de Ambato|Ambato]] prison cell in 1980.\n\nLaytner's interviews were widely published, first in the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' on Sunday, 13 July 1980, then in the ''[[Toronto Sun]]'' and ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'' on 21 July 1980, and over the years in many other North American papers and foreign publications, including the ''[[National Enquirer]]''. Apart from Laytner's account and two brief [[Associated Press]] wire reports,<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|url=http://users.erols.com/mwhite28/lopez_ap.htm |title=Who is Pedro Lopez? |accessdate=2013-08-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021224003/http://users.erols.com/mwhite28/lopez_ap.htm |archivedate=21 October 2007 }}</ref> the story was published in ''The World's Most Infamous Murders'' by Boar and Blundell,<ref>The World's Most Infamous Murders by Roger Boar and Nigel Blundell \u2013 Octopus London 1983 {{ISBN|0-600-57008-8}} pages 116\u2013118</ref> and has found its way into many serial murder anthologies, both in print and online.\n\nAccording to Laytner's story,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.editinternational.com/read.php?id=47ddbd11af56e |title=Worst Serial Killer Released |publisher=Edit International |accessdate=2013-08-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710172222/http://www.editinternational.com/read.php?id=47ddbd11af56e# |archive-date=10 July 2011 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> L\u00f3pez became known as the '''Monster of the Andes''' in 1980, when he led police to 53 graves in [[Ecuador]]. The victims were all girls 12 years of age. In 1983, he was found guilty of the murder of 110 girls in [[Ecuador]]. He further confessed to an additional 240 murders in [[Peru]] and [[Colombia]].\n\n==Early life==\nL\u00f3pez's mother was a prostitute named Benilda L\u00f3pez De Casteneda. According to L\u00f3pez, witnessing acts of prostitution while growing up had disturbing effects on his psyche. Subsequently, his mother caught him fondling his younger sister in 1957, when he was eight years old, and evicted him from the family home.<ref name=\"NineNews\">{{cite web |last1=Pearson |first1=Nick |title=World's second worst serial killer walked free from prison |url=https://www.9news.com.au/world/pedro-lopez-worlds-second-worst-serial-killer-walked-free-from-prison/2be19c5c-95c5-44e2-8dd1-3253319a34e5 |website=Nine News |accessdate=30 November 2019 |date=5 December 2018}}</ref> Following this, L\u00f3pez fled to [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia's capital city. He says he was picked up by a man, taken to a deserted house and repeatedly sodomized. At age twelve, he was taken in by an American family and enrolled in a school for orphans. He ran away after two years because he was allegedly molested by a male teacher. An alternative account says he ran away with a teacher. At 18, he stole cars for a living and sold the cars to local [[chop shop]]s.{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\n==Murders==\nDuring his incarceration for car theft, L\u00f3pez claimed he was brutally gang-raped<ref name=\"NineNews\"/> and that he hunted down his rapists and killed the most brutal while still in prison. He said that after his jail term, he started murdering young girls in Peru. He claimed that, by 1978, he had killed over 100 of them and that he had been caught by a native tribe, who were preparing to execute him, when an American Christian missionary intervened and persuaded them to hand him over to the state police. The police soon released him. He said he moved to Colombia and later Ecuador, killing about three girls a week. L\u00f3pez said: \"I like the girls in Ecuador; they are more gentle and trusting. More innocent.\"\n\n==Arrest==\nL\u00f3pez was arrested when an attempted abduction failed and he was trapped by market traders. The [[Associated Press]] (AP) reported that he was arrested in March 1980, and that he confessed to killing 103 girls, including 53 whose bodies had been found. In January 1981, he was convicted of three murders, and had confessed to three hundred [[sexual assault]]s and stranglings.<ref name=\"AP\" /> The police only believed his confessions when a flash flood uncovered a mass grave containing many of his victims.<!-- or according to the near-contemporary news article one grave was exposed by a flash flood - or according to A&E the flash flood was before his arrest--> \n\n==Release==\nAccording to the BBC, L\u00f3pez \"was arrested in 1980, but was freed by the government in Ecuador at the end of [1998].\"  In an interview from his prison cell, L\u00f3pez described himself as \"the man of the century\" and said he was being released for \"good behavior.\" An A&E ''[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]'' documentary reported that he was released from an Ecuadorian prison on 31 August 1994, then rearrested  as an illegal immigrant and handed over to Colombian authorities, who charged him with a 20-year-old murder. He was declared insane and held in the psychiatric wing of a Bogot\u00e1 hospital. In 1998, he was declared sane and released on $50 bail, subject to certain conditions. He later absconded. The same documentary says that [[Interpol]] released an advisory for his rearrest by Colombian authorities over a fresh murder in 2002,<ref name=\"A&E\">{{Cite video|title=The Monster of the Andes|date=2004|ISBN=0-7670-7897-7|publisher=A&E Television Networks|author=Carlina Ramon; Maria Masabanda Inde; Carlos J\u00e1come; Pat Brennan}}</ref> and he is currently wanted by the police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vocal.media/criminal/why-did-they-free-pedro-lopez-the-monster-of-the-andes|title=Why Did They Free Pedro L\u00f3pez, the Monster of the Andes?|website=Criminal|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>\n\nThere is currently a shortage of information regarding L\u00f3pez. His whereabouts are unknown as of 2020.<ref name=\"bio.com\">{{cite web |url= http://www.biography.com/people/pedro-alonso-lopez-12103226 |title= Pedro Alonzo Lopez Biography |website= [[biography.com]] |date= 2018-01-31 |accessdate= 2018-01-31 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161210235245/http://www.biography.com/people/pedro-alonso-lopez-12103226# |archive-date= 10 December 2016 |url-status= live |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Coverage==\nThe 2006 edition of the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' credited Lopez as being the \"most prolific serial killer\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-prolific-serial-killer|title=Most prolific serial killer|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216093053/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/most-prolific-serial-killer |archive-date=2015-02-16}}</ref> The listing was removed after complaints that it made a competition out of murder, as well as comments that it overlooked killers such as [[Thug Behram]], who reportedly murdered around 900 people in India.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=k5FY0LJL6NkC</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of fugitives from justice who disappeared]]\n* [[List of serial killers by number of victims]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez, Pedro}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:1980s murders in Colombia]]\n[[Category:1980s murders in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:1983 crimes in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:1983 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:1990s murders in Colombia]]\n[[Category:1998 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:2000s murders in Colombia]]\n[[Category:2002 crimes in Colombia]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:20th-century criminals]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse in Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Colombian murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Colombian people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:Colombian people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Colombian prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Colombian rapists]]\n[[Category:Colombian serial killers]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Colombia]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n", "name_user": "Intrested2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedro_L%C3%B3pez_(serial_killer)"}
